      <h2 id='dataqs'>How we get our data</h2>

      <div class="qgroup">

        <div class="panel-group" id="Haccordion" role="tablist" aria-multiselectable="true">

          <div class="panel panel-default">
            <div class="panel-heading" role="tab" id="headingHOne">
              <h3 class="panel-title">
                <a class="q" data-toggle="collapse" data-parent="#accordion" href="#collapseHOne" aria-expanded="false" aria-controls="collapseHOne">
                  Where do you get your directions information from?
                </a>
              </h3>
            </div>
            <div id="collapseHOne" class="panel-collapse collapse" role="tabpanel" aria-labelledby="headingHOne">
              <div class="panel-body">
                <p class="answer">
                  We use the Google Maps API for all driving, transit, and walking directions. To learn more about Google Maps, please visit <a href="http://www.google.com/maps/about/">http://www.google.com/maps/about/</a>.
                </p>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="panel panel-default">
            <div class="panel-heading" role="tab" id="headingHTwo">
              <h3 class="panel-title">
                <a class="q" data-toggle="collapse" data-parent="#accordion" href="#collapseHTwo" aria-expanded="false" aria-controls="collapseHTwo">
                  Where do you get your carbon estimates from?
                </a>
              </h3>
            </div>
            <div id="collapseHTwo" class="panel-collapse collapse" role="tabpanel" aria-labelledby="headingHTwo">
              <div class="panel-body">
                <p class="answer">
                  For the calculations, we found statistics from 2014 from <a href="http://www.eia.gov/tools/faqs/faq.cfm?id=307&t=10">the US Energy Information Administration</a> and <a href="http://www.ecopassenger.org/">ecopassenger.org</a> to use as measurements for how much carbon dioxide is emitted depending on fuel consumption and method of travel. Then, we take the distance we got from Google Maps and do lots of algebra.
                  <br><br>
                  For example, since the average car* has an average mileage of 23mpg (37km per gallon), we use the distance of the user's trip and then divide by 37 to calculate how many gallons of gasoline fuel the car would consume. Then, using the statistic that 8.7 kg of CO2 is emitted per gallon of gas, we multiplied the number of gallons by 8.7 to get the total CO2 emission.
                  <br><br>
                  For the transit travel mode, we found that commuter rail trains, light rail trains, heavy rail trains, etc. all have relatively similar CO2 emissions per individual, so we just used the statistic .2 lbs of CO2 is emitted per mile on a train, converted that to kg (.9 kg per mile), and then multiplied that by the distance travelled to get the CO2 emission of a train ride.
                  <br><br>
                  For flights, there is a difference in CO2 emission depending on the length of the trip, so we took the average of short, medium, and long flights and got .23kg per mile flown, and then multiplied that by the distance travelled to get the CO2 emission of a flight.
                  <br><br>
                  While these measurements are by no means perfect, we believe that this info provides a reasonable estimate of the carbon emissions you use while travelling, and more importantly, can help you make more informed decisions regarding your carbon footprint.
                  <br><br>
                  *At this time, we are unable to give you the option of saving your car(s)' fuel efficiency.
                </p>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

        </div><!--end collapsible panels-->

