      <h2 id='mapqs'>Google Maps related questions</h2>

      <div class="qgroup">

        <div class="panel-group" id="Maccordion" role="tablist" aria-multiselectable="true">

          <div class="panel panel-default">
            <div class="panel-heading" role="tab" id="headingMOne">
              <h3 class="panel-title">
                <a class="q" data-toggle="collapse" data-parent="#accordion" href="#collapseMOne" aria-expanded="false" aria-controls="collapseMOne">
                  Why is it giving me the <i>wrong</i> address/city/country?
                </a>
              </h3>
            </div>
            <div id="collapseMOne" class="panel-collapse collapse" role="tabpanel" aria-labelledby="headingMOne">
              <div class="panel-body">
                <p class="answer">
                  Did you enter the correct address? If so, your search might not be specific enough. For example, you might not have entered the city, state, zip code, or country associated with the address. 
                  <br><br>
                  Your location might also have something to do with this too. According to the <a href="https://developers.google.com/maps/documentation/geocoding/#RegionCodes">Google Maps API</a> (which we use for GreenBuggle), "the Google Geocoding API returns address results influenced by the region (typically the country) from which the request is sent. For example, searches for 'San Francisco' may return different results if sent from a domain within the United States than one sent from Spain."
                </p>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="panel panel-default">
            <div class="panel-heading" role="tab" id="headingMTwo">
              <h3 class="panel-title">
                <a class="q" data-toggle="collapse" data-parent="#accordion" href="#collapseMTwo" aria-expanded="false" aria-controls="collapseMTwo">
                  Why won't it calculate the transit directions?
                </a>
              </h3>
            </div>
            <div id="collapseMTwo" class="panel-collapse collapse" role="tabpanel" aria-labelledby="headingMTwo">
              <div class="panel-body">
                <p class="answer">
                  Google might not have added your city yet. To check, please visit <a href="https://maps.google.com/landing/transit/cities/">Google Maps | Transit | Cities covered</a>. If your city isn't covered, you might not be able to use the transit feature on GreenBuggle, and you might have to look up the website for your city's transit agency for directions instead. We apologize for the inconvenience.
                  <br><br>
                  Plus, sometimes there is no transit option from certain cities to other cities, e.g. Montreal, Canada, to Mexico City, Mexico.
                </p>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="panel panel-default">
            <div class="panel-heading" role="tab" id="headingMThree">
              <h3 class="panel-title">
                <a class="q" data-toggle="collapse" data-parent="#accordion" href="#collapseMThree" aria-expanded="false" aria-controls="collapseMThree">
                  Why won't it calculate the driving directions from, say, NYC to London?
                </a>
              </h3>
            </div>
            <div id="collapseMThree" class="panel-collapse collapse" role="tabpanel" aria-labelledby="headingMThree">
              <div class="panel-body">
                <p class="answer">
                  As far as we know, they haven't built a long bridge from North America to Europe yet, nor can most cars drive underwater, so you probably couldn't drive across the Atlantic Ocean anyway. But more specifically, Google Maps seems to have retired the old directions of "swim across X ocean" from circa 2007, and the current Maps regional specifications won't give directions from North America to Europe.
                  <br><br>
                  Some other regional limitations (that we have noticed; this has not been confirmed) include driving directions from China to anywhere else, Australia to anywhere else, Southeast Asia to East Asia or the Middle East, and North to South America.
                  <br><br>
                  Also, occasionally a location is simply too small or isolated for Google to give good directions to/from there.
                </p>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="panel panel-default">
            <div class="panel-heading" role="tab" id="headingMFour">
              <h3 class="panel-title">
                <a class="q" data-toggle="collapse" data-parent="#accordion" href="#collapseMFour" aria-expanded="false" aria-controls="collapseMFour">
                  OK, so what <i>can</i> I do on the GreenBuggle map?
                </a>
              </h3>
            </div>
            <div id="collapseMFour" class="panel-collapse collapse" role="tabpanel" aria-labelledby="headingMFour">
              <div class="panel-body">
                <p class="answer">
                  Because we were curious to the limitations of Google Maps, we tried some random searches and found the following:
                </p>
                <ul class="answer">
                  <li>You can get driving/walking directions from Magadan, Russia (eastern Russia) to Cape Town, South Africa.</li>
                  <li>You can get driving/walking directions from Magadan, Russia to Lisbon, Portugal.</li>
                  <li>You can get driving/walking directions from Oslo, Norway to Johannesburg, South Africa.</li>
                  <li>You can get driving/walking directions from Juneau, Alaska to Panama City, Panama, but not South America.</li>
                  <li>You can get driving/walking directions from Caracas, Venezuela to Puntas Arenas, Chile.</li>
                  <li>You can occasionally get driving/walking directions from island to island within countries, e.g. Okinawa, Japan, to Tokyo, Japan, though these routes may include ferries.</li>
                </ul>
                <p class="answer">
                  <br>Please note, however, that we are unlikely to generate accurate data for directions of such long distances.
                </p>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
          </div>

